ᾗ 4. nullum ante finem. The long delay and heavy losses of the siege may well have disgusted Hannibal with operations which gave so little scope for his genius for strategy. We find therefore that in Italy he rarely persevered in the siege of any of the fortresses by which he passed in his campaigns. He marched too rapidly through hostile country to carry with him the heavy materials of a siege train.

ξ 4. fieri non p. The chronological difficulty existed only in the authorities which Livy followed. The account of Poly- bius is clear and consistent, agreeing only with L. in the eight months for the siege, and the five for the march to Italy. He makes the Roman envoys reach H. at Carthago Nova before the siege begins, and throws back the embassy of Saguntum to the year before the consulship of Scipio and Sempronius.
